WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:08.120
Okay, thank you very much and thanks for coming.

00:00:08.120 --> 00:00:13.960
So we are going to, the title of this talk was Leveraging LLMs for Student Feedback in

00:00:13.960 --> 00:00:20.879
Introductory Data Science Courses, but in short I'm going to call this Help from AI.

00:00:20.879 --> 00:00:23.000
And let's see how far we can get with that.

00:00:23.000 --> 00:00:31.719
So to provide some context, I teach, I used to teach it every semester, now at least once

00:00:31.719 --> 00:00:32.720
a year.

00:00:32.720 --> 00:00:37.599
One of our largest courses at the university, which is the Introductory Data Science course,

00:00:37.599 --> 00:00:43.080
and this course is made up of sort of five learning modules where we start the students

00:00:43.080 --> 00:00:50.200
off, introducing them to mostly the toolkit and the ideas in the Hello World section and

00:00:50.200 --> 00:00:58.560
the toolkit is comprised of R, RStudio, Corto for writing reproducible reports, so every

00:00:58.560 --> 00:01:02.959
single assignment is developed in that, and also Git as well.

00:01:02.959 --> 00:01:07.400
So every single assignment is turned in as a Git repository.

00:01:07.400 --> 00:01:12.279
We try to circumvent our learning management system as much as possible, but don't tell

00:01:12.279 --> 00:01:16.000
people outside of this building I said so.

00:01:16.000 --> 00:01:21.480
Then we go to our exploring data unit where we start by visualizing data, take a step

00:01:21.480 --> 00:01:25.639
back and say what if it's not ready to be visualized, so what if we need to get it into

00:01:25.639 --> 00:01:30.199
the right shape, take another step back and say what if we don't even have it, but it's

00:01:30.199 --> 00:01:35.760
in a tabular format and you can use a single function to read it in, or it's very unstructured

00:01:35.760 --> 00:01:41.620
and on the web and we need to scrape it and getting it into a tabular format.

00:01:41.620 --> 00:01:46.620
This brings us to the ethics unit, which is placed there for two reasons.

00:01:46.620 --> 00:01:52.099
One is that I did not want it to be an afterthought at the end of the semester, which is where

00:01:52.099 --> 00:01:57.540
it used to be when I first started teaching this course, and number two, it plays really

00:01:57.540 --> 00:02:02.339
nicely after web scraping to stop and ask now that you've learned some tools for web

00:02:02.339 --> 00:02:07.839
scraping and you've learned some tools for checking whether the website owner is okay

00:02:07.959 --> 00:02:12.160
with you scraping these data, should you really be scraping these data.

00:02:12.160 --> 00:02:15.279
That brings us to our ethics discussion.

00:02:15.279 --> 00:02:20.399
We talk about data privacy, but also things like misrepresenting data science results

00:02:20.399 --> 00:02:22.720
and algorithmic bias as well.

00:02:22.720 --> 00:02:28.520
Not necessarily teaching them the algorithms per se, but just giving them some intuition

00:02:28.520 --> 00:02:35.639
around making decisions with models before we actually dive into the modeling unit.

00:02:35.639 --> 00:02:41.039
The third unit, or the fourth unit, is perhaps the more traditionally statistical unit where

00:02:41.039 --> 00:02:46.639
we start by trying to understand what do we mean by a statistical model.

00:02:46.639 --> 00:02:53.039
We focus quite a bit on predictive models in this class, so classification as well,

00:02:53.039 --> 00:02:58.479
and then we end with statistical inference in this unit, and we keep our discussion to

00:02:58.479 --> 00:03:04.039
simulation-based statistical inference, and at the very end of that conversation say every

00:03:04.039 --> 00:03:09.360
single bell curve that you've been seeing every time you bootstrapped or did a randomization

00:03:09.360 --> 00:03:12.520
test was not there by happenstance.

00:03:12.520 --> 00:03:17.559
There is statistical theory that grounds all of this, so please take another class where

00:03:17.559 --> 00:03:19.639
you can learn about those.

00:03:19.639 --> 00:03:24.039
The last unit is the looking further unit where, depending on how much time is left

00:03:24.039 --> 00:03:30.240
in the semester, we dive into things either I am interested in diving into or the students

00:03:30.240 --> 00:03:35.960
are interested in diving into, so that's somewhere on the order of two or three lectures,

00:03:35.960 --> 00:03:39.759
and students are also working on their projects at that time.

00:03:39.759 --> 00:03:42.880
You can see the communicate thread throughout.

00:03:42.880 --> 00:03:51.399
One thing I will say about this course is that no number or plot or table is reported

00:03:51.399 --> 00:03:54.100
without some narrative that goes along with it.

00:03:54.100 --> 00:03:59.800
That narrative can be a whole write-up, that narrative can be a sentence or two, but everything

00:03:59.800 --> 00:04:04.759
gets interpreted, so the assessment of the student work is not limited to checking the

00:04:04.759 --> 00:04:11.800
code they used to develop something, but also what they wrote about the final numbers or

00:04:11.800 --> 00:04:15.440
distributions or whatever they have come up with.

00:04:15.440 --> 00:04:21.600
This is in fall 2024 when I taught this course what my grading scheme looked like, and for

00:04:21.600 --> 00:04:27.619
many, many years I have been a firm believer in, maybe still am a firm believer in, sort

00:04:27.619 --> 00:04:32.220
of not putting all of the weight on exams and giving students an opportunity to sort

00:04:32.220 --> 00:04:40.619
of accrue those points in assignments that they can do at home on their own time, come

00:04:40.619 --> 00:04:44.899
to office hours for help when they're stuck, so on and so forth.

00:04:44.899 --> 00:04:51.140
The thing is, when you look at this as a student, that is a very high weight attached to something

00:04:51.140 --> 00:04:57.220
that can take you a lot of time or that can take you much less time to turn in maybe mediocre

00:04:57.220 --> 00:05:03.420
work if you have an assistant that will happily barf out code for you.

00:05:03.420 --> 00:05:07.700
This was my AI policy, and I will say, let me go through that real quick.

00:05:07.700 --> 00:05:12.899
I said, you can use AI tools for code, but you must cite it, and I provided some guidance

00:05:12.899 --> 00:05:18.100
for how to cite it, and I said the prompt used can't be copied and pasted from the assignment.

00:05:18.100 --> 00:05:19.100
How am I going to police that?

00:05:19.100 --> 00:05:23.739
I can't, but I said it anyway just to have said it.

00:05:23.739 --> 00:05:30.899
I said you can't use AI tools for narrative, so words like sentences you write must be

00:05:30.899 --> 00:05:37.140
your own words, and I said for your learning, I don't know, do whatever you want to do,

00:05:37.140 --> 00:05:42.179
and I think this was all too optimistic ultimately.

00:05:42.179 --> 00:05:49.779
So this led us to sort of think about, I don't know, how can we maybe more productively use

00:05:49.779 --> 00:05:50.779
AI tools?

00:05:50.820 --> 00:05:59.540
So project one, honestly, was sort of like both inspired by sort of developments at the

00:05:59.540 --> 00:06:04.619
university, particularly Mark McHale, who had been supporting our course for the computational

00:06:04.619 --> 00:06:09.899
infrastructure for a while, coming and saying, like, we have some resources to work on some

00:06:09.899 --> 00:06:12.380
AI-driven things.

00:06:12.380 --> 00:06:13.959
Is there something we could do?

00:06:13.959 --> 00:06:19.859
And also, my sort of goal that if students are going to use AI tools for learning, is

00:06:19.940 --> 00:06:25.019
there a way we can keep bringing them back to the course materials that we keep asking

00:06:25.019 --> 00:06:27.980
them and assigning them to read and nobody's reading?

00:06:27.980 --> 00:06:33.440
So the goal was to build a chatbot that hopefully generates good, helpful, and correct answers

00:06:33.440 --> 00:06:39.540
that come from course content, so it prefers terminology, syntax, methodology, and workflows

00:06:39.540 --> 00:06:42.980
that are actually taught in the course.

00:06:42.980 --> 00:06:47.220
The first motivation is because the course size has been increasing over the years.

00:06:47.220 --> 00:06:52.660
You can kind of see where the course sizes, we teach over 600 students a semester, but

00:06:52.660 --> 00:06:57.940
our TA sizes isn't growing, you know, as exponentially over this time.

00:06:57.940 --> 00:07:06.019
Therefore, we may not always have as much support as the students might be needing.

00:07:06.019 --> 00:07:12.500
The other motivation was that I asked, like, could we generate good answers comparable

00:07:12.579 --> 00:07:20.260
to answers from the course instructor or TA that actually stays current with course content?

00:07:20.260 --> 00:07:25.380
In my opinion, one of the challenges of the wild, wild west of all the LLM tools out there

00:07:25.380 --> 00:07:30.739
is that they will happily give answers to you, but they're sort of like sampling from

00:07:30.739 --> 00:07:34.179
this much wider space than my course alone.

00:07:34.179 --> 00:07:41.140
So here's an example of how would you sort of like do a task, a particular task in R.

00:07:41.220 --> 00:07:49.779
In this case, we're trying to sort of like fix this or clean this membership status variable, for example.

00:07:49.779 --> 00:07:54.899
This course is taught using tidyverse syntax, and for those with a keen eye, you will see

00:07:54.899 --> 00:07:57.459
that there's none of that here.

00:07:57.459 --> 00:08:01.380
And in fact, there's some functions here that, I don't know, at least does not ever come

00:08:01.380 --> 00:08:04.260
up in my course, like set diff, for example.

00:08:04.260 --> 00:08:09.299
So when students get answers like this, I get two types of reactions.

00:08:09.299 --> 00:08:12.339
One, this must be good enough.

00:08:12.339 --> 00:08:18.100
Number two, how dare she expect me to write this, given what she has taught me?

00:08:18.100 --> 00:08:22.179
And that latter one is really hard to answer, because it's absolutely true.

00:08:22.179 --> 00:08:28.179
If this was the correct answer to a question, I have not been teaching them in the right way.

00:08:28.179 --> 00:08:31.059
But it is difficult when you're entirely new to this.

00:08:31.059 --> 00:08:36.099
Like many of you in this room might look at this and say, that's not tidyverse code.

00:08:36.099 --> 00:08:41.140
And you can then say, and that's base R code, and it's good or not good.

00:08:41.140 --> 00:08:46.020
To my students who have not done any programming before, it's just this looks different than

00:08:46.020 --> 00:08:47.140
what I have learned.

00:08:47.140 --> 00:08:52.659
Why have I not been prepared to read this answer that's given to me?

00:08:52.659 --> 00:09:03.539
So the technical details was that basically we wanted to create this chat bot that is

00:09:03.539 --> 00:09:06.179
augmented with course materials.

00:09:06.179 --> 00:09:15.700
And then that is also going to bring us back to the course materials when students actually

00:09:15.700 --> 00:09:16.820
ask a question to it.

00:09:16.820 --> 00:09:17.940
And I'll be very honest.

00:09:17.940 --> 00:09:20.659
I have not implemented the model underneath it myself.

00:09:20.659 --> 00:09:23.059
Actually, Mark, who is in this room, who has.

00:09:23.059 --> 00:09:31.700
So I'll show the graphic that he had developed to give you an idea of what's happening.

00:09:31.700 --> 00:09:33.700
And this chat bot is not publicly available.

00:09:33.700 --> 00:09:39.460
We've put this behind the Canvas, the learning management system for the course.

00:09:39.460 --> 00:09:44.979
And the main reason for that is that one of the other things that in terms of these AI

00:09:44.979 --> 00:09:51.619
tools that I often think about is the equity aspect of like, should your learning be determined

00:09:51.619 --> 00:09:56.260
by whether you can put down a credit card at some point to get more answers?

00:09:56.260 --> 00:10:00.580
And we wanted to make sure that any student in the class had access to this.

00:10:00.580 --> 00:10:04.739
And sometimes that means we want to make sure no one else has access to it so we can

00:10:04.739 --> 00:10:06.659
properly support the students in the class.

00:10:07.380 --> 00:10:13.539
So we started with PDF documents that come from the course materials, the open interest

00:10:13.539 --> 00:10:17.619
statistics textbook, and the R for data science textbook.

00:10:17.619 --> 00:10:20.580
And then we built the knowledge graph based off of that.

00:10:20.580 --> 00:10:27.299
And so whenever a student asks a question, that's the user query you're seeing on this

00:10:27.299 --> 00:10:30.260
diagram here, two things are happening.

00:10:30.260 --> 00:10:32.900
One, that question is getting logged.

00:10:32.900 --> 00:10:36.179
And number two, student gets an answer.

00:10:36.179 --> 00:10:40.340
And so we have logs of each of these threads of these questions.

00:10:40.340 --> 00:10:45.219
And in case this question comes up, I can't answer the question, how did learning like

00:10:45.219 --> 00:10:45.859
change?

00:10:45.859 --> 00:10:47.539
These are completely de-identified.

00:10:47.539 --> 00:10:52.659
And the students knew that I had access to their questions and that I did not have a

00:10:52.659 --> 00:10:57.539
way of connecting those to their student IDs.

00:10:57.539 --> 00:11:02.020
And I guess they trusted me on it because remember that don't copy and paste thing?

00:11:03.059 --> 00:11:04.179
You know, you get the idea.

00:11:04.900 --> 00:11:09.219
So I can't answer the question about student learning and using this tool.

00:11:09.219 --> 00:11:13.940
Maybe that's an interesting exploration, but we wanted to go forth with this without

00:11:13.940 --> 00:11:15.859
thinking through IRB implications.

00:11:16.659 --> 00:11:18.739
Therefore, we never identified the students.

00:11:19.539 --> 00:11:22.020
So here's a quick demo of what something looks like.

00:11:22.020 --> 00:11:24.020
So a student asks a question.

00:11:24.020 --> 00:11:25.940
It's thinking for a while.

00:11:25.940 --> 00:11:29.700
And then you're going to see that it sort of gives us an answer.

00:11:29.700 --> 00:11:32.260
And I'm going to try to pause the video here.

00:11:32.260 --> 00:11:36.500
But so we have an answer that's written up that should seem very familiar for anyone

00:11:36.500 --> 00:11:38.500
who has used a chatbot interface.

00:11:38.500 --> 00:11:41.299
But you're also seeing on the side the resources.

00:11:41.299 --> 00:11:46.900
Now, that is not all of the resources the model may have used to generate those sentences.

00:11:46.900 --> 00:11:50.340
There's a lot, obviously, to generate those sentences happening.

00:11:50.340 --> 00:11:54.020
But those are the course resources that things are grabbed from.

00:11:54.020 --> 00:11:57.940
So for a student, what this does is they read about it a little bit.

00:11:57.940 --> 00:12:02.580
And in front of their eyeballs is the resources from the course materials that they can come

00:12:02.580 --> 00:12:03.059
back to.

00:12:03.059 --> 00:12:08.580
And my hope being that this brings them back to those materials to say, oh, it is in the

00:12:08.580 --> 00:12:09.219
book.

00:12:09.219 --> 00:12:10.659
Maybe I should read the chapter.

00:12:10.659 --> 00:12:15.619
Or maybe if they keep getting directed back to the same chapter, at some point they start

00:12:15.619 --> 00:12:18.340
thinking, this is the chapter I may want to reread.

00:12:18.340 --> 00:12:20.179
Maybe the others are good for me.

00:12:20.179 --> 00:12:23.219
And similarly, a question about R syntax.

00:12:23.219 --> 00:12:27.380
How do we read data from Excel into R?

00:12:27.380 --> 00:12:32.900
Now it brings us to pages from the R for Data science book, similarly.

00:12:32.900 --> 00:12:36.900
Obviously, there are many other things it could be pointing to off the web.

00:12:36.900 --> 00:12:39.619
But the goal is to bring them back to the course materials.

00:12:41.140 --> 00:12:45.219
Here's some data from the fall 2024 class.

00:12:45.219 --> 00:12:50.099
This is very crude data analysis of the students' questions.

00:12:50.099 --> 00:12:51.940
But let's take a look at the word counts.

00:12:52.500 --> 00:12:56.580
There is some questions that are way long.

00:12:56.580 --> 00:13:02.260
And when I look at those questions, it's like, all of this stuff R spit out to me.

00:13:02.260 --> 00:13:05.299
I put it into this to see if it can help me make sense of it.

00:13:05.299 --> 00:13:07.619
So fix this code, and then a bunch of code.

00:13:09.380 --> 00:13:13.059
In the middle are mostly verbatim questions from the assignments.

00:13:13.059 --> 00:13:17.859
This is why I figured they believed when I told them I can't identify you,

00:13:17.859 --> 00:13:20.340
because I had told them explicitly not to do that.

00:13:20.340 --> 00:13:22.900
But then here are mostly good interactions.

00:13:22.900 --> 00:13:26.099
And what I mean by that, and not the shortest amount,

00:13:26.099 --> 00:13:30.820
is that these were threads where the students were going back and forth and saying,

00:13:30.820 --> 00:13:32.419
but wait, what about that?

00:13:32.419 --> 00:13:33.619
And how do you do this?

00:13:33.619 --> 00:13:36.580
And that's sort of a nice interaction, I think,

00:13:36.580 --> 00:13:40.900
as long as we can direct them back to the course resources, especially.

00:13:41.299 --> 00:13:44.419
Now, this then brought me to thinking about,

00:13:44.419 --> 00:13:49.219
where else can we use this same model that we have built to support the course?

00:13:49.940 --> 00:13:52.820
And the idea was to build a feedback bot.

00:13:52.820 --> 00:13:54.900
So let's think about what that means.

00:13:54.900 --> 00:14:00.340
Now, an ever-increasing number of students are using AI tools as their first step

00:14:00.340 --> 00:14:02.900
before thinking about how to approach a task

00:14:02.900 --> 00:14:05.539
has been my experience teaching this course.

00:14:06.500 --> 00:14:11.219
So that moment at the end of, I read question one,

00:14:12.179 --> 00:14:15.700
and I want to start writing my answer to question one,

00:14:15.700 --> 00:14:18.979
that is exactly where I am hoping to interject

00:14:19.539 --> 00:14:24.500
and see if we can help something to happen other than copying and pasting.

00:14:28.340 --> 00:14:30.900
This is one of the studies, somewhat recent,

00:14:30.900 --> 00:14:35.780
that found that AI makes human cognition atrophied and unprepared.

00:14:35.780 --> 00:14:39.460
But there's been more of these over the last few months as well,

00:14:39.460 --> 00:14:43.780
of just saying that the more folks are using these tools,

00:14:43.780 --> 00:14:45.780
the differently they're using their brains,

00:14:45.780 --> 00:14:49.859
and differently, at least from what we understand to be good learning nowadays.

00:14:51.219 --> 00:14:53.619
Motivation two, though, is to say,

00:14:53.619 --> 00:14:57.940
well, that doesn't mean maybe they shouldn't use it at all.

00:14:57.940 --> 00:15:00.340
I, at least for the course that I'm teaching,

00:15:00.340 --> 00:15:03.460
and the things that I'm intellectually interested in,

00:15:03.460 --> 00:15:08.179
I'm not in a land of absolutely zero use of AI tools,

00:15:08.179 --> 00:15:12.580
but I would hope for them to use it in a way that can enrich their learning,

00:15:12.580 --> 00:15:15.780
and maybe also to gain us some TA time as well.

00:15:17.219 --> 00:15:21.859
Instead of making the TAs do some of the feedback giving to students,

00:15:22.739 --> 00:15:26.179
redistribute their time to the one-on-one student interaction.

00:15:26.179 --> 00:15:28.820
So really, I want AI to do my laundry,

00:15:28.820 --> 00:15:31.780
so I can do art, not the other way around, is what I mean.

00:15:32.500 --> 00:15:35.380
And number three is self-motivation, self-care.

00:15:36.419 --> 00:15:38.900
I don't want to read chat GPT answers.

00:15:38.900 --> 00:15:43.059
Like, I am very happy to read edited chat GPT answers

00:15:43.059 --> 00:15:46.020
that have been made better by a student writing.

00:15:46.020 --> 00:15:47.460
I don't want to read that.

00:15:47.460 --> 00:15:49.859
And we have actually put our teaching assistants

00:15:49.859 --> 00:15:53.700
who do much of the grading for this course in a very bizarre situation,

00:15:53.700 --> 00:15:56.979
where we tell them their performance is measured,

00:15:56.979 --> 00:16:00.179
in part, by quality of their feedback,

00:16:00.739 --> 00:16:03.219
but what they're giving feedback to is not real humans.

00:16:03.219 --> 00:16:05.539
And those humans are probably not reading that feedback

00:16:05.539 --> 00:16:07.460
if they never wrote the code in the first place.

00:16:07.460 --> 00:16:10.900
So it's a very funny and not nice place to be in.

00:16:11.619 --> 00:16:16.179
And I have to write these awfully detailed rubrics nonetheless.

00:16:16.739 --> 00:16:19.539
So a little bit of TLDR,

00:16:19.539 --> 00:16:22.500
but the technical details is that we can use Elmer,

00:16:22.500 --> 00:16:27.700
the R package that Hadley talked about for interfacing with an LLM,

00:16:27.700 --> 00:16:29.299
to give it a system prompt.

00:16:29.299 --> 00:16:32.500
So this is a shortened version of the system prompt

00:16:32.500 --> 00:16:34.099
to fit onto the screen,

00:16:34.099 --> 00:16:37.059
but the idea is you're a helpful course instructor

00:16:37.059 --> 00:16:39.140
and you like to give succinct feedback.

00:16:40.260 --> 00:16:42.500
Read the question, read the rubric,

00:16:43.219 --> 00:16:44.900
and read the student answer,

00:16:45.460 --> 00:16:48.500
and give feedback against this rubric, okay?

00:16:49.460 --> 00:16:53.380
And basically, we're using that same model as before,

00:16:53.380 --> 00:16:58.260
and we're going to be sort of like logging the student data as we go as well.

00:16:58.260 --> 00:16:59.380
So let's take a look.

00:16:59.380 --> 00:17:03.700
A question on fit a linear regression model and interpret the coefficients.

00:17:03.700 --> 00:17:06.339
I've purposefully picked this example

00:17:06.339 --> 00:17:10.500
because the answer is not a single number that we're sort of measuring against,

00:17:10.500 --> 00:17:12.260
so there's some narrative as well.

00:17:13.300 --> 00:17:17.060
This is what the student's answer might look like, for example.

00:17:17.140 --> 00:17:18.739
So they have written some code,

00:17:18.739 --> 00:17:23.780
so part A is code, part B is a model like write up,

00:17:23.780 --> 00:17:27.540
and part C and D are narrative answers.

00:17:27.540 --> 00:17:29.859
So we're sending it all at once.

00:17:31.459 --> 00:17:33.219
And this is the demo rubric.

00:17:33.219 --> 00:17:35.619
So you can see how detailed this rubric is.

00:17:35.619 --> 00:17:39.300
This is really the rubric we've been using to grade this question,

00:17:39.300 --> 00:17:43.060
like code does this, narrative does this, so on and so forth.

00:17:43.459 --> 00:17:46.500
And here's what the feedback from the AI tool looks like.

00:17:46.500 --> 00:17:49.300
So it picks the rubric items that we had,

00:17:50.180 --> 00:17:54.979
and then it writes a short narrative next to it saying,

00:17:54.979 --> 00:17:57.300
you have met this or you have not met this.

00:17:58.260 --> 00:17:59.619
I'll give you another example.

00:17:59.619 --> 00:18:01.780
So this was for a regression question.

00:18:03.780 --> 00:18:06.579
This was for a data tidying question,

00:18:06.579 --> 00:18:10.260
and here we had instructed the tool to actually categorize

00:18:11.219 --> 00:18:13.939
as met, partially met, or not met,

00:18:13.939 --> 00:18:16.579
to sort of draw the student's attention a little bit.

00:18:17.140 --> 00:18:19.699
And so take a look at a few things here.

00:18:19.699 --> 00:18:22.420
So this is basically a pivot task.

00:18:22.420 --> 00:18:25.219
So it catches, oh, you haven't named the variable

00:18:25.219 --> 00:18:27.939
or the data frame the way you've been asked to name it,

00:18:27.939 --> 00:18:30.660
which is, you know, it should be an easy thing to spot.

00:18:30.660 --> 00:18:35.140
But it also says something about code style and readability,

00:18:36.099 --> 00:18:38.500
which turns out actually was a hallucination.

00:18:39.140 --> 00:18:41.459
The student's code style was perfectly fine.

00:18:41.459 --> 00:18:45.459
So while this looks plausible, this is not perfect feedback either.

00:18:46.180 --> 00:18:50.339
But I've also not seen, I teach a class of 330 students,

00:18:50.339 --> 00:18:53.939
I don't see 330 perfect feedback from human TAs,

00:18:53.939 --> 00:18:56.819
including myself either, to be perfectly honest.

00:18:57.459 --> 00:18:59.859
So quickly, the takeaways.

00:18:59.859 --> 00:19:04.180
In terms of the process, lots of fiddling with the rubric file

00:19:04.180 --> 00:19:07.459
to land at a place where things are starting to look happy.

00:19:07.459 --> 00:19:11.060
But at some point, you ask yourself, could I go forever with this?

00:19:12.099 --> 00:19:15.540
But separating out the rubric and the rubric detailed

00:19:15.540 --> 00:19:18.900
helped to not give the correct answers away every time.

00:19:20.020 --> 00:19:22.660
The good was it sort of works.

00:19:22.660 --> 00:19:26.660
And in terms of the bad, I think the most concerning is that

00:19:26.660 --> 00:19:31.060
it tends to catch errors, but not the good answers.

00:19:31.060 --> 00:19:34.500
So the students might sometimes feel like there's no winning here,

00:19:35.060 --> 00:19:37.380
which they do sometimes feel in a classroom.

00:19:37.859 --> 00:19:41.300
But I think it's really important that I would categorize this

00:19:41.300 --> 00:19:46.819
on order of experience feedback from an inexperienced TA,

00:19:46.819 --> 00:19:50.020
which we have many of, until they get more experienced, obviously.

00:19:50.660 --> 00:19:54.180
The inevitable is inconsistency from one run to another.

00:19:54.180 --> 00:19:56.660
But humans also are inconsistent.

00:19:56.660 --> 00:19:58.979
And as I mentioned, hallucinations do happen.

00:20:00.420 --> 00:20:02.260
And then it says really annoying things.

00:20:02.260 --> 00:20:04.579
This doesn't align with rubric expectations.

00:20:04.579 --> 00:20:07.699
What a nugget to give to students to be pissed off with me.

00:20:08.420 --> 00:20:12.739
They would come to me and be like, what are your expectations, obviously.

00:20:12.739 --> 00:20:15.140
But I want to emphasize, this is not grading.

00:20:15.140 --> 00:20:19.380
It's just to provide some feedback to the students so they can get better.

00:20:19.380 --> 00:20:21.939
So I'm hoping that that's going to be a good thing.

00:20:22.500 --> 00:20:24.660
So I will skip over these for now.

00:20:24.660 --> 00:20:28.500
And I just want to acknowledge Mark and Duco IT for supporting this.

00:20:29.459 --> 00:20:33.060
And we're going to be running this experiment in fall 2025,

00:20:33.060 --> 00:20:36.260
actually, in the course for part of the course content.

00:20:36.260 --> 00:20:45.140
So ask me again in January how I feel about the whole thing.

